accreditation

Loop variable for technician ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (technician), this variable (accreditation) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
<td>{{ task.status_changed_inspected|date}}</td> <td> {% for accreditation in technician.accreditations %} <div></div> {% endfor %}
Loop variable for tasksession ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (tasksession), this variable (accreditation) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
{{ tasksession.finished|timezone:tasksession.timezone|date:'H:iA'|default:"(still in progress)" }}</td> <td> {% for accreditation in tasksession.technician.accreditations %} <div>{{accreditation.name}}: {{ accreditation.number }}</div> {% endfor %}

bc

Loop variable for report ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (report), this variable (bc) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
<tr> <th>Class of Building:</th> <td>{% for bc in report.property.building_classes %}{{ bc }}{% if not forloop.last %}, {% endif %}{% empty %}{{ report.property.building_class }}{% endfor %}</td> <th>Building Era:</th> <td>{{ property.building_era }}</td>

  • Price
  • Qty
thorfire
  • Standard Invoice
  • Flow Test Report - Hydrants

  • Mitie Invoice

  • Invoice
  • Invoice
  • Invoice MOD
  • Annual Certification WA (ASMR)
  • Invoice
  • Invoice
  • Invoice
  • Invoice
Usage Examples 

{% if bc.is_fixed %}
<dt>Billing Period</dt>
<dd>{{ bc|bc_get_period_begin:invoice.task }} - {{ bc|bc_get_period_end:invoice.task }}</dd>
{% endif %}
{% endif %}


{% if bc.is_fixed %}
<dt>Billing Period</dt>
<dd>{{ bc|bc_get_period_begin:invoice.task }} - {{ bc|bc_get_period_end:invoice.task }}</dd>
{% endif %}
{% endif %}

category

Loop variable for category_list ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (category_list), this variable (category) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
<tbody> {% regroup productlineitems by product.category as category_list %} {% for category in category_list %} <tr> <td rowspan="{{ category.list|length }}">{{ category.grouper|default:'-' }}</td>

  • test sq

list.0.quantity{{ category.list.0.quantity|floatformat:2 }}
list.0.subtotal{{ category.list.0.subtotal|currency }}
list.0.unit_price{{ category.list.0.unit_price|currency }}

char

Loop variable for config ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (config), this variable (char) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
<div class="w-50"> <div class="organisation">{{ config.SITE_ORGANISATION }}</div> <div>{% for char in config.CONTACT_ADDRESS %}{% if char == "," %}<br>{% else %}{{ char }}{% endif %}{% endfor %}</div> <div>Tel: {{ config.CONTACT_PHONE }}</div> <div>Email: accounts@econogard.com</div>

Loop variable for servicequote ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (servicequote), this variable (document) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:

form_response

Loop variable for form_responses ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (form_responses), this variable (form_response) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
{% load dynamicforms_helpers %} {% get_form_responses task=task for_form="Grainger - AC Form" as form_responses %} {% for form_response in form_responses %} {{ form_response.render|safe }} {% endfor %}

item

Loop variable for items ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (items), this variable (item) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
{% regroup report.get_items|order_by_key:'type.name' by type as items_by_type %} {% for type, items in items_by_type %} {% for item in items %} {% ifchanged item.label %} <tr>
Loop variable for contractor ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (contractor), this variable (item) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
<tr> <td> {% for item in contractor.list %} <div>- {{ item.label }}</div> {% endfor %}
Loop variable for product_group ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (product_group), this variable (item) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
<td class="text-right"> {% with total_gst=0 %} {% for item in product_group.list %} {% with total_gst=total_gst|add:item.gst %} {% endwith %}

line

Loop variable for productlineitems ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (productlineitems), this variable (line) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
</thead> <tbody> {% for line in productlineitems %} <tr class="keep-together"> <td>{{ line.product.name }}</td>

What this means:

Example:
</td> </tr> {% for line in servicelineitems %} {% if line.routineservicetype and line.billingcontract_type == "F" %} <tr class="keep-together">
Loop variable for lineitems ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (lineitems), this variable (line) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
</thead> <tbody> {% for line in lineitems %} <tr> <td><div>{{ line.product }}</div>

What this means:

</thead> <tbody> {% for line in serviceitems %} <tr class="keep-together"> <td>{{ line.description|default:'-' }}</td>

Loop variable for lineitems ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (lineitems), this variable (lineitem) represents each individual item as we process the list.

</thead> <tbody> {% for lineitem in lineitems %} <tr> <td class="text-left">{{ lineitem.quantity|floatformat:2 }}</td>

What this means:
When working with a collection (lineitem_group), this variable (lineitem) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
</thead> <tbody class="table-striped table-bordered"> {% for lineitem in lineitem_group.lineitems %} <tr> <td>{{ lineitem.description|markdowner|default:lineitem.product.description }}</td>

{% endfor %} {% for creditnote in invoice.creditnote_set.all %} {% for lineitem in creditnote.lineitems.all %} <tr> <td>{{ lineitem.description|markdowner }}</td>

lineitem_group

Loop variable for consolidated_tasks ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (consolidated_tasks), this variable (lineitem_group) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
</thead> <tbody class="table-striped table-bordered"> {% for lineitem_group in consolidated_tasks %} {% if lineitem_group.task %} <tr>

list_item

Loop variable for lineitems ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (lineitems), this variable (list_item) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
{% for product_type, lineitems in lineitem_list %} {% if product_type != "R" and product_type != "M" %} {% for list_item in lineitems %} <tr> <td class="text-left">{{ list_item.description }}</td>

photo

Loop variable for before_photos ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (before_photos), this variable (photo) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
{% if before_photos %} <div><strong>Before Photos</strong></div> {% for photo in before_photos %} {% get_overlay_for_photo report photo as overlay %} <div>
Loop variable for after_photos ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (after_photos), this variable (photo) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
<div class="mw-50"> <strong>After</strong><br> {% for photo in after_photos %} <a class="d-inline-block mt-1" style="margin-right: 0.5px;" href="{% cdn_image_url photo.path type="authenticated" %}"> {% cdn_image photo.path width=50 height=50 crop="fill" type="authenticated" %}
Loop variable for task_photos ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (task_photos), this variable (photo) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
<div class="m-3" > <div class="d-flex flex-row" style="display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap;"> {% for photo in task_photos %} {% include "webtemplates/2022-photo-tile" with photo=photo class="mr-1 mt-1" %} {% endfor %}
Loop variable for photos ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (photos), this variable (photo) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
{% if photos %} <div class="d-block photo-row my-1"> {% for photo in photos %} <a class="d-block" href="{% cdn_image_url photo.path type="authenticated" %}"> {% cdn_image photo.path width=90 height=90 crop="limit" type="authenticated" %}
Loop variable for asset_photos ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (asset_photos), this variable (photo) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
</a> {% empty %} {% for photo in asset_photos %} <a class="mx-1 mb-2" href="{% cdn_image_url photo.path type="authenticated" %}"> {% cdn_image photo.path width=125 height=175 crop="fill" type="authenticated" %}
Loop variable for remark_photos ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (remark_photos), this variable (photo) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
<td colspan="3"> <div class="d-flex flex-wrap"> {% for photo in remark_photos %} <a class="mx-1 mb-2" href="{% cdn_image_url photo.path type="authenticated" %}"> {% cdn_image photo.path width=125 height=175 crop="fill" type="authenticated" %}

product_group

Loop variable for lineitems_by_product ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (lineitems_by_product), this variable (product_group) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
<tbody> {% regroup lineitems|order_by_key:"product.name" by product.name as lineitems_by_product %} {% for product_group in lineitems_by_product %} <tr> <td>{{ product_group.grouper }}</td>
Found in files

  • Purchase Order

  • Purchase Order V2
Attributes
AttributeExample Usage
grouper{{ product_group.grouper }}
list{{ product_group.list|sum_list:"subtotal"|currency }}
list.0{{ product_group.list.0|get_lineitem_tax_code }}
list.0.product.sku{{ product_group.list.0.product.sku }}
list.0.unit_price{{ product_group.list.0.unit_price|currency }}

rem

Loop variable for severity_remarks ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (severity_remarks), this variable (rem) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
<tr> <td width="5%" class="critical text-white"><strong> {% for rem in severity_remarks %} {% if rem.grouper == 10 %} {{rem.list|length}}

remark

Loop variable for item ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (item), this variable (remark) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
<tbody> {% for item in items|visible %} {% for remark in item.get_all_remarks %} <tr> <td>{{ remark.location|default:"Throughout" }}</td>
Loop variable for prompt ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (prompt), this variable (remark) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
{{ prompt.answer.reason }} {% elif prompt.answer.remarks.exists %} {% for remark in prompt.answer.remarks.all %} <span class="d-block"> <strong>{{ remark.get_severity_display }}</strong>
Loop variable for all_remarks ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (all_remarks), this variable (remark) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
<table width="100%" class="remark-table mb-3"> <tbody> {% for remark in all_remarks %} <tr> <td colspan="3" class="p-0">
Loop variable for servicetask ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (servicetask), this variable (remark) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
{% if servicetask.service_item.get_all_remarks %} <ul class="list-unstyled mb-0"> {% for remark in servicetask.service_item.get_all_remarks %} {% if not remark|has_promptanswers %} <li>
Loop variable for system ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (system), this variable (remark) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
<div> <span class="text-muted label">System defects:</span> {% for remark in system.defects %} <div><a target="_blank" href="{{ remark.get_public_url|absolute }}">{{ remark.ref }}</a> {{ remark.get_description|truncatechars:50 }}</div> {% empty %}

schedule

Loop variable for property ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (property), this variable (schedule) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
<p>Occupancy permit:</p> <table class="table no-border schedule-list-table"> {% for schedule in property.schedule_set.all %} <tr> <th width="30%">Type</th>
Loop variable for schedules ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (schedules), this variable (schedule) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
{% if schedules %} <div><span>This report is in relation to </span> {% for schedule in schedules %} {% if not forloop.first and not forloop.last %} <span>, </span>

st

Loop variable for stproducts ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (stproducts), this variable (st) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
<strong>Materials used</strong> <ul class="mb-0"> {% for st in stproducts %} <li>{{ st.product }}</li> {% endfor %}
Loop variable for servicetasks ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (servicetasks), this variable (st) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
</thead> <tbody> {% for st in servicetasks %} <tr> <td>{{ st.product.name|default:"-" }}</td>

tasksession

Loop variable for labour_sessions ?
What this means:
When working with a collection (labour_sessions), this variable (tasksession) represents each individual item as we process the list.

Example:
<br></br> {% get_labour_sessions_for_task report as labour_sessions %} {% for tasksession in labour_sessions %} <p><b>Legal representative:</b> {{ tasksession.technician }}</p> <p><b>Signature:</b>{% render_signature_on_file tasksession.technician.id|stringformat:'d' %}</p>
